# Responsive Design Rule

**Whenever the design is changed, you must also check the responsive.css file.**

## Core Principles
- All design changes must consider both desktop and mobile layouts
- Responsive breakpoints must be maintained across all screen sizes
- Menu functionality and positioning must work on all devices
- Font sizes and layouts must adapt appropriately

## Main Style Files
- **Primary:** `css/style.css` - Main stylesheet containing desktop/tablet styles
- **Responsive:** `css/responsive.css` - Contains all responsive breakpoints and mobile-specific styles

## Breakpoints in responsive.css
- **Desktop/Tablet:** `@media (min-width: 992px) and (max-width: 1199px)`
- **Tablet:** `@media (min-width: 768px) and (max-width: 991px)`
- **Large Mobile:** `@media (min-width: 576px) and (max-width: 767px)`
- **Mobile:** `@media (max-width: 575px)`

## Key Responsive Elements
- `.toggle_menu` - Menu positioning changes across breakpoints
- `.togle_3` - Register/Login elements hidden on mobile
- `.banner_taital` - Font sizes adjust for different screen sizes
- `.menu_text` - Menu container width and positioning

## Examples

### ✅ Correct: Checking Both Files
```css
/* style.css - Desktop styles */
.banner_taital {
    font-size: 38px;
    color: #181919;
}

/* responsive.css - Mobile adjustments */
@media (max-width: 575px) {
    .banner_taital { 
        font-size: 32px; 
    }
}
```

### ❌ Incorrect: Only Changing Desktop Styles
```css
/* style.css - Only desktop changes */
.banner_taital {
    font-size: 45px; /* Changed but no mobile consideration */
}

/* Missing responsive.css updates for mobile */
```

### ✅ Correct: Menu Positioning
```css
/* style.css */
.toggle_menu {
    top: 8px;
    position: relative;
}

/* responsive.css */
@media (max-width: 575px) {
    .toggle_menu { 
        top: -35px; 
        float: right; 
    }
}
```

### ❌ Incorrect: Breaking Mobile Menu
```css
/* style.css */
.toggle_menu {
    position: absolute;
    right: 0;
    /* This breaks mobile layout */
}

/* Missing responsive override */
```

## Implementation Guidelines

### Checklist for Design Changes:
1. ✅ Make changes to `style.css` (desktop styles)
2. ✅ Check `responsive.css` for corresponding breakpoints
3. ✅ Update responsive styles if needed
4. ✅ Test across different screen sizes
5. ✅ Ensure mobile menu functionality remains intact

### Common Responsive Issues to Avoid:
- Menu positioning (`float: right` on mobile)
- Font size adjustments for readability
- Layout changes (column stacking on mobile)
- Element hiding/showing based on screen size

## Benefits
- Maintains consistent user experience across all devices
- Prevents layout breaking on mobile devices
- Ensures proper menu functionality on touch devices
- Keeps typography readable on small screens

**Remember:** Any design change that affects layout, positioning, or styling must be checked against all responsive breakpoints to maintain consistency across devices.
